# Bill of Materials (BOM)

Complete parts list for the LED Chess Board project with specifications, quantities, and sourcing information.

**Total Project Cost:** ~$75

## Core Electronics

| Component | Part Number/Model | Quantity | Unit Cost | Purpose |
|-----------|------------------|----------|-----------|---------|
| Arduino Mega 2560 | ELEGOO | 1 | ~$15 | Main microcontroller |
| CD74HC4067 Multiplexer | 16-channel | 4 | ~$1 each | I/O expansion for LED control |
| 1kΩ Resistor (¼W) | - | 4 | <$0.10 each | Current limiting for LED protection |
| Pre-wired SMD Micro LEDs | Various colors | 75 (3×25pcs) | ~$8 per 25 | Square indicators |

### Component Details

#### Arduino Mega 2560 (ELEGOO)

**Specifications:**
- Microcontroller: ATmega2560
- Operating Voltage: 5V
- Digital I/O Pins: 54 (15 provide PWM output)
- Analog Input Pins: 16
- Flash Memory: 256 KB
- SRAM: 8 KB
- Clock Speed: 16 MHz

**Why This Board:**
- Sufficient I/O pins (54 vs. Uno's 14) for multiplexer control
- Adequate memory (256 KB) for chess algorithm implementation
- Stable 3.3V output for LED power
- USB interface for programming and serial communication

#### CD74HC4067 Multiplexers

**Specifications:**
- Channels: 16 (individually selectable)
- Control Inputs: 4-bit binary (S0-S3)
- Operating Voltage: 2V to 6V
- Enable Pin: Active LOW
- Switching Speed: High-speed CMOS
- Package: DIP or breakout board

**Functionality:**
- Reduces 16 I/O lines to 5 pins (4 control + 1 signal)
- Bidirectional operation (can read or write)
- Low ON-state resistance
- High OFF-state isolation

**Why 4 Multiplexers:**
- 64 squares ÷ 16 channels = 4 multiplexers needed
- Each MUX controls one 4×4 quadrant of the board

#### 1kΩ Resistors

**Specifications:**
- Resistance: 1000Ω (±5% tolerance)
- Power Rating: ¼W
- Type: Carbon film or metal film

**Purpose:**
- Current limiting for LED protection
- One resistor per multiplexer signal pin
- Prevents excessive current draw from Arduino

**Current Calculation:**
```
I = V / R = 3.3V / 1000Ω = 3.3mA per LED
Safe operating range for typical LEDs: 2-20mA
```

#### Pre-wired SMD Micro LEDs

**Specifications:**
- Size: SMD micro (compact for under-tile mounting)
- Colors: Red, Yellow, Green (25 each)
- Pre-soldered leads: Simplifies installation
- Forward Voltage: ~2-3V
- Forward Current: ~20mA (max)

**Design Choice:**
- Pre-wired construction saves soldering time
- Small size fits beneath chess tiles
- Multiple colors available for move indication (optional)

## Structural Components

| Component | Material | Quantity | Purpose |
|-----------|----------|----------|---------|
| Prototyping Boards | FR4 PCB | 4 | Circuit organization and MUX mounting |
| Chess Tiles | 3D Printed PLA | 32 Light / 32 Dark | Playing surface with LED holes |
| Chess Board Base | Laser Cut Acrylic | 1 box | Housing for circuitry |
| Chess Pieces | Clear Plastic | 1 set (32 pieces) | Physical game interface |

### Structural Details

#### Prototyping Boards

**Specifications:**
- Type: Perforated PCB breadboard
- Size: Sufficient for 2 multiplexers each
- Hole Spacing: Standard 0.1" (2.54mm)
- Material: FR4 fiberglass

**Features:**
- Through-hole connections
- Solderable pads
- Easy wire routing and bridging

**Layout:**
- 2 multiplexers per board
- Component spacing for 1kΩ resistor mounting
- Wire routing channels

#### 3D Printed Chess Tiles

**Design Features:**
- Center hole for LED mounting
- Standard chess square size (~2" per side, adjustable)
- Alternating light/dark colors for board pattern
- Slightly raised edges for piece positioning

**Material:**
- PLA filament (recommended)
- Light colors: White, cream, or tan
- Dark colors: Black, brown, or gray

#### Acrylic Base

**Purpose:**
- Contains and protects circuitry
- Provides rigid mounting surface
- Elevates playing surface above electronics

**Design:**
- Box construction with open top
- Access panel for Arduino USB connection
- Cable routing holes
- Sufficient depth for prototyping boards and wiring

## Wiring and Connectors

| Component | Specification | Quantity | Purpose |
|-----------|--------------|----------|---------|
| Hookup Wire | 22 AWG solid/stranded | ~50 feet | Connections |
| Heat Shrink Tubing | Various sizes | 3-4 feet | Insulation |
| Solder | 60/40 tin-lead or lead-free | 1 spool | Permanent connections |

### Wiring Recommendations

**Wire Colors (Suggested):**
- Red: +3.3V / Signal pins
- Black: Ground
- Blue: Control signals (S0-S3)
- Green: Enable pins
- Other colors: LED connections

**Wire Gauge:**
- 22 AWG: Good balance of flexibility and current capacity
- Solid core: Easier for prototyping board connections
- Stranded: Better for Arduino pin headers

## Tools Required (Not Included)

- Soldering iron (temperature controlled recommended)
- Solder wick or desoldering pump
- Wire strippers
- Diagonal cutters
- Needle-nose pliers
- Multimeter (for continuity testing)
- Heat gun or lighter (for heat shrink)
- Third hand or PCB holder

## Optional Components

| Component | Purpose | Cost |
|-----------|---------|------|
| LED holders/clips | More secure LED mounting | ~$5 |
| Cable management clips | Neater wire routing | ~$3 |
| Rubber feet | Anti-slip base padding | ~$2 |
| Power supply | External power if USB insufficient | ~$10 |

## Sourcing Recommendations

**Electronics:**
- Amazon, DigiKey, Mouser for components
- ELEGOO official store for Arduino
- SparkFun or Adafruit for multiplexer breakouts

**Structural:**
- Local makerspace for 3D printing and laser cutting
- Hardware store for acrylic sheets (if cutting yourself)
- Online chess retailers for pieces

## Assembly Cost Breakdown

| Category | Approximate Cost |
|----------|-----------------|
| Electronics | $30-35 |
| Structural Components | $25-30 |
| Wiring/Connectors | $10-15 |
| Miscellaneous | $5-10 |
